The "specter of Kant keeps surfacing in thinkers like Putnam and Habermas who are convinced that reason cannot be naturalized" (Berstein 59). The "novel twist" comes from John McDowell. Berstein says that \'93at first glance, it seems that McDowell fits right into the tradition of Kantian anti-naturalism \'97 a tradition that runs from Kant right up to Putnam and Habermas\'94 since he thinks \'93reason can\'92t be naturalized\'94 (Bernstein 62). But his arguments, Berstein thinks, against bald naturalism amount to some sophisticated question-begging via sleight of hand. %\
