## Summary\
\
**Chapter 4. Virtue as excellence of practical reason, practical wisdom.** The third chapter presents an account of practical reason according to which practical wisdom (the excellence of practical reason) is a necessary condition of all the other virtues. Questions I aim to answer include: what is practical reason and what is excellence in regard to it?[@foot2001natural, chapter 4; @mcdowell1979virtue]  Can moral reasons satisfy the "practical requirement" with regard to morality? Is practical reason egoistic or can we undermine the distinction between 'self-regarding' and 'other-regarding' virtues[@slote1995agent], between self-love and conscience?[@annas2009egoism; @macintyre1967egoism; @bloomfield2012eudaimonia; @huang2010self] Are the deliverances of practical reasoning subjective, intersubjective, or objective? Are we rational? What about *akrasia*? What is foolishness? Is it relative to cultures? How do we keep reason objective but liberal, plural but not anarchic. The good is true but even first we pursue truth because it is good. The value of truth.\
